WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.340
This is a LibriVox recording. All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:06.080 --> 00:11.200
For more information visit www.librivox.org.

00:12.840 --> 00:19.600
Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson. Chapter 29. The Black Spot Again.

00:21.320 --> 00:26.240
The Council of Buccaneers had lasted some time when one of them re-entered the house,

00:26.240 --> 00:30.720
and with a repetition of the same salute which had in my eyes an

00:30.720 --> 00:34.280
ironical air, begged for a moment's loan of the torch.

00:35.500 --> 00:41.000
Silver briefly agreed, and this emissary retired again, leaving us together in the dark.

00:42.180 --> 00:48.060
There's a breeze coming, Jim, said Silver, who had by this time adopted quite a friendly

00:48.060 --> 00:53.060
and familiar tone. I turned to the loophole nearest me and looked out.

00:53.060 --> 00:59.380
The embers of the great fire had so far burned themselves out and now glowed so low and duskily

00:59.380 --> 01:03.440
that I understood why these conspirators desired a torch.

01:04.540 --> 01:10.880
About halfway down the slope to the stockade they were collected in a group. One held the light,

01:11.400 --> 01:17.780
another was on his knees in their midst, and I saw the blade of an open knife shine in his hand

01:17.780 --> 01:21.020
with varying colors in the moon and torchlight.

01:22.060 --> 01:26.520
The rest were all somewhat stooping as though watching the maneuvers of this last.

01:27.600 --> 01:31.680
I could just make out that he had a book as well as a knife in his hand,

01:32.140 --> 01:36.820
and was still wondering how anything so incongruous had come in their possession

01:36.820 --> 01:43.140
when the kneeling figure rose once more to his feet and the whole party began to move together

01:43.140 --> 01:44.280
towards the house.

01:45.160 --> 01:51.560
Here they come, said I, and I returned to my former position, for it seemed beneath my dignity

01:51.560 --> 01:53.900
that they should find me watching them.

01:54.740 --> 02:01.280
Well, let them come, lad, let them come, said Silver cheerfully. I've still a shot in my locker.

02:02.620 --> 02:08.200
The door opened and the five men standing huddled together just inside pushed one of

02:08.200 --> 02:14.880
their number forward. In any other circumstances it would have been comical to see his slow advance,

02:15.360 --> 02:21.000
hesitating as he set down each foot, but holding his closed right hand in front of him.

02:21.680 --> 02:28.920
Step up, lad, cried Silver. I won't eat you. Hand it over, lover. I know the rules I do.

02:29.060 --> 02:30.880
I won't hurt your deputation.

02:32.860 --> 02:38.340
Thus encouraged, the buccaneer stepped forward more briskly, and having passed something to Silver

02:38.340 --> 02:43.240
from hand to hand, slipped yet more smartly back again to his companions.

02:44.500 --> 02:46.680
The seacook looked at what had been given him.

02:47.240 --> 02:54.580
The black spot, I thought so, he observed. Where might ye have got the paper? Why,

02:54.580 --> 03:01.900
look here now. This ain't lucky. You've gone and cut this out of a Bible. What fools cut a Bible.

03:03.060 --> 03:09.340
Ah, there, said Morgan, there. What did I say? No good'll come of that, I said.

03:10.700 --> 03:13.780
Well, you've about fixed it now among you,

03:14.560 --> 03:20.460
continued Silver. You'll all swing now, I reckon. What soft-headed lubber had a Bible?

03:21.240 --> 03:27.760
It was Dick, said one. Dick was it? Then Dick can get to prayers, said Silver.

03:28.820 --> 03:32.140
He's seen his slice of luck as Dick, and you may lay to that.

03:33.320 --> 03:36.480
But here the long man with the yellow eyes struck in.

03:37.020 --> 03:43.380
Belay that talk, Silver, he said. This crew has tipped you the black spot in full counsel,

03:43.740 --> 03:49.760
as in duty bound. Just you turn it over, as in duty bound, and see what's wrote there.

03:49.760 --> 03:56.720
Then you can talk. Thank ye, George, replied the sea cook. You've always was brisk for business,

03:56.760 --> 04:02.360
and has the rules at heart, George, as I'm pleased to see. Well, what is it, anyway?

04:04.320 --> 04:11.540
Ah, deposed. That's it, is it? Very pretty wrote, to be sure. Like print, I swear.

04:12.220 --> 04:17.860
Your hand aright, George? Why, you was getting quite a leadin' man in this here crew.

04:17.860 --> 04:24.220
You'll be captain next, I shouldn't wonder. Just oblige me with that torch again, will you?

04:24.240 --> 04:33.360
This pipe don't draw. Come now, said George, you don't fool this crew no more. You're a funny man

04:33.360 --> 04:39.180
by your account, but you're over now, and you'll maybe step down off that barrel and help vote.

04:40.300 --> 04:47.380
I thought you said you knowed the rules, returned Silver contemptuously. Least ways if you don't,

04:47.380 --> 04:54.000
I do, and I wait here, and I'm still your captain, mind, till you outs with your grievances,

04:54.000 --> 05:01.020
and I reply, in the meantime, your black spot ain't worth a biscuit. After that, we'll see.

05:02.060 --> 05:10.460
Oh, replied George, you don't be under no kind of apprehension. We're all square we are. First,

05:10.480 --> 05:17.280
you've made a hash of this cruise. You'll be a bold man to say no to that. Second, you let

05:17.280 --> 05:23.480
the enemy out of this here trap for nothin'. Why did they want out? I don't know, but it's

05:23.480 --> 05:30.800
pretty plain they wanted it. Third, you wouldn't let us go with them upon the march. Oh, we see

05:30.800 --> 05:37.560
through you, John Silver. You want to play booty, that's what's wrong with you. And then, fourth,

05:38.140 --> 05:43.720
there's this here boy. Is that all? asked Silver quietly.

05:44.500 --> 05:50.660
Enough, two, retorted George. We'll all swing and sundry for your bungling.

05:52.300 --> 05:56.880
Well, now, look here. I'll answer these far pints one after another, I'll answer them.

05:57.380 --> 06:03.640
I made a hash of this cruise, did I? Well, now, you all know what I wanted, and you all know if

06:03.640 --> 06:08.860
that had been done that we'd have been aboard the Hispagnola this night as ever was, every man of

06:08.860 --> 06:14.340
us alive and fit and full of good plum duff, and the treasure in the hold of her by thunder.

06:15.500 --> 06:22.420
Well, who crossed me? Who forced my hand as was the lawful captain? Who tipped me the black spot

06:22.420 --> 06:28.840
the day we landed and began this dance? Ah, it's a fine dance, I'm with you there, and looks mighty

06:28.840 --> 06:36.060
like a hornpipe in a rope's end at Execution Dock, my London town it does. But who done it? Why,

06:36.060 --> 06:42.600
it was Anderson and Hans and you, George Mary, and you're the last aboveboard of that same

06:42.600 --> 06:48.680
meddling crew, and you have the Davy Jones insolence to have up and stand for captain over me,

06:49.000 --> 06:55.540
you that sank the lot of us? By the powers, but this tops the stiffest yarn to nothing.

06:57.280 --> 07:03.140
Silver paused, and I could see by the faces of George and his late comrades that these words had

07:03.140 --> 07:09.920
been said in vain. That's for number one, cried the accused, wiping the sweat from his brow,

07:10.260 --> 07:15.480
for he had been talking with the vehemence that shook the house. Why, I give you my word,

07:15.500 --> 07:21.580
I'm sick to speak to you. You've neither sense nor memory, and I leave it to fancy where your

07:21.580 --> 07:28.550
mother's was that let you come to see. See, gentlemen of fortune, I reckon Taylor's is your

07:28.550 --> 07:37.410
aid. Go on, John, said Morgan, speak up to the others. Ah, the others, returned John.

07:38.430 --> 07:44.370
They're a nice lot, ain't they? You say this cruise is bungled? Ah, by gum, if you could

07:44.370 --> 07:50.590
understand how bad it's bungled, you would see. We're that near the gibbet that my neck's stiff

07:50.590 --> 07:56.710
with thinking on it. You've seen them, maybe, hanged in chains, birds about them, seamen

07:56.710 --> 08:02.370
pointing them out as they go down with the tide. Who's that, says one? That, why, that's John

08:02.370 --> 08:08.690
Silver. I knowed him well, said another. And you can hear the chains a-jangle as you go about and

08:08.690 --> 08:14.310
reach for the other buoy. Now, that's about where we are, every mother's son of us, thanks to him

08:14.310 --> 08:21.470
and Hans and Anderson and other ruination fools of you. And if you want to know about number four,

08:21.470 --> 08:28.330
and that boy, why, shiver me timbers, isn't he a hostage? Are we going to waste a hostage?

08:28.730 --> 08:36.250
No, not us. He might be our last chance and I wouldn't wonder. Kill that boy, not me, mates.

08:37.050 --> 08:43.570
And number three, ah, well, there's a deal to say to number three. Maybe you don't count it

08:43.570 --> 08:50.170
nothing to have a real college doctor to see you every day, you, John, with your head broke, or you,

08:50.170 --> 08:56.410
George, Mary, that had the og shakes about you not six hours ago, and has your eyes the color of

08:56.410 --> 09:02.410
lemon peel to this same moment of the clock. And maybe, perhaps, you didn't know there was a consort

09:02.410 --> 09:09.270
coming either. But there is, and not so long till then, and we'll see who'll be glad to have a

09:09.270 --> 09:16.710
hostage when it comes to that. And as for number two, and why I made a bargain, well, you came

09:16.710 --> 09:24.370
crawling on your knees to me to make it. On your knees you came. You was downhearted and you'd have

09:24.370 --> 09:31.790
starved, too, if I hadn't. But that's a trifle. You look there, that's why. And he cast down upon

09:31.790 --> 09:38.250
the floor a paper that I instantly recognized, none other than the chart on yellow paper with

09:38.250 --> 09:43.390
the three red crosses that I had found in the oilcloth at the bottom of the captain's chest.

09:43.950 --> 09:47.410
Why the doctor had given it to him was more than I could fancy.

09:48.350 --> 09:54.010
But if it were inexplicable to me, the appearance of the chart was incredible to the surviving

09:54.010 --> 10:00.790
mutineers. They leaped upon it like cats upon a mouse. It went from hand to hand, one tearing

10:00.790 --> 10:05.790
it from another. And by the oaths and the cries and the childish laughter with which they

10:05.790 --> 10:10.830
accompanied their examination, you would have thought not only were they fingering the very gold,

10:10.830 --> 10:18.170
but were at sea with it besides in safety. Yes, said one, that's flint, sure enough.

10:18.430 --> 10:23.150
J.F. and a score below with the clove hitched to it. So he done ever.

10:24.750 --> 10:30.670
Mighty pretty, said George, but how are we to get away with it and us no ship?

10:31.930 --> 10:36.430
Silver suddenly sprang up and supporting himself with a hand against the wall.

10:36.990 --> 10:42.570
Now I give you warning, George, he cried. One more word of your sauce and I'll call you down

10:42.570 --> 10:48.770
and fight you. How? Why, how do I know? You would ought to tell me that. You and the rest

10:48.770 --> 10:54.970
that lost me my schooner with your interference burn you. But not in you you can't. You ain't got

10:54.970 --> 11:01.010
the invention of a cockroach. But civil you can speak and shall, George Mary, you may lay to that.

11:01.770 --> 11:04.530
Now that's fair enough, said the old man Morgan.

11:05.930 --> 11:12.590
Fair, I reckon so, said the sea cook. You lost the ship, I found the treasure. Who's the better man

11:12.590 --> 11:19.230
at that? And now I resign by thunder. Elect whom you please to be your captain now. I'm done with

11:19.230 --> 11:27.870
it. Silver, they cried. Barbecue forever. Barbecue for captain. So that's the tune as it cried the

11:28.670 --> 11:34.310
George, I reckon you'll have to wait another turn friend and lucky for you as I'm not a revengeful

11:34.310 --> 11:42.930
man, but that never was my way. And now shipmates, this black spot, taint much good now, is it?

11:43.350 --> 11:47.890
Dick's crossed his luck and spoiled his Bible and that's about all.

11:49.090 --> 11:57.850
It'll do to kiss the book on still, won't it? growled Dick, who was evidently uneasy at the

11:57.850 --> 12:04.770
Bible with a bit cut out, returned Silver derisively. Not it. It won't buy no more in a

12:04.770 --> 12:12.690
ballot book. Don't it though? cried Dick with a sort of joy. Well, I reckon that's worth having too.

12:14.370 --> 12:18.930
Here Jim, here's a curiosity for you, said Silver and he tossed me the paper.

12:20.010 --> 12:26.070
It was around the size of a crown piece. One side was blank for it had been the last leaf.

12:26.070 --> 12:32.310
The other contained a verse or two of Revelation. These words among the rest which struck sharply

12:32.310 --> 12:40.530
home upon my mind. Without are dogs and murderers. The printed side had been blackened with wood ash

12:40.530 --> 12:46.050
which already began to come off and soil my fingers. On the blank side had been written

12:46.050 --> 12:53.110
with the same material the one word deposed. I had that curiosity beside me at this moment,

12:53.110 --> 12:59.470
but not a trace of writing now remains beyond a single scratch such as a man might make with

12:59.470 --> 13:06.410
his thumbnail. That was the end of the night's business. Soon after with a drink all round we

13:06.410 --> 13:12.250
lay down to sleep and the outside of Silver's vengeance was to put George Mary up for sentinel

13:12.250 --> 13:19.230
and threaten him with death if he should prove unfaithful. It was long ere I could close an eye

13:19.230 --> 13:24.730
and heaven knows I had matter enough for thought in the man whom I had slain that afternoon

13:24.730 --> 13:31.770
in my most perilous position and above all in the remarkable game that I saw Silver now engaged upon

13:31.770 --> 13:37.770
keeping the mutineers together with one hand and grasping with the other after every means

13:37.770 --> 13:45.410
possible and impossible to make his peace and save his miserable life. He himself slept peacefully

13:45.410 --> 13:52.750
and snored aloud yet my heart was sore for him, wicked as he was, to think on the dark perils

13:52.750 --> 13:58.830
that environed and the shameful gibbet that awaited him. End of chapter 29

